FORGEZERO PERFORMANCE NOTES
===========================

BENCHMARK PROFILE
-----------------
ForgeZero is designed for large, incremental builds where the cost of
orchestration dominates the cost of individual compiler invocations.

The implementation targets three main bottlenecks: task scheduling, cache
locality, and file I/O.

MULTI-LEVEL CACHE
-----------------
ForgeZero uses a three-tier action cache:
- L1: in-memory metadata for the hottest entries
- L2: memory-mapped data for larger working sets
- L3: on-disk archives for persisted results

This layout keeps the fast path fast while still allowing recovery across
process boundaries.

OS AND I/O ACCELERATORS
-----------------------
MAP_POPULATE
    On Linux, mapped cache files are opened with MAP_POPULATE to reduce
    page-fault overhead during large scans.

io_uring
    When FORGEZERO_IO_URING=1 is set on supported Linux systems, the I/O
    layer can use io_uring for file reads and writes. The implementation falls
    back to the standard library automatically when the backend is unavailable.

PREFETCH
    The builder uses explicit prefetch instructions on supported x86_64 builds
    to reduce cache-miss latency in hot loops.

PARALLEL LINKING
----------------
For larger object sets, ForgeZero can partition outputs and link them through
the same DAG scheduler used for compilation.

HASHING AND CONFIG PARSING
--------------------------
- BLAKE3 hashing is pooled and reused across worker goroutines.
- TOML parsing is cached by file metadata to avoid redundant startup cost.
- Config includes and profiles are resolved once and reused across the build
  session.
